<br>
<i>Judge Jackson began by questioning Schmalensee's assertion that if Microsoft was a monopoly operating with the kind of power alleged by the government, it would charge computer manufacturers (OEMs) as much as $2,000 for a copy of Windows instead of the current price of approximately $50. Schmalensee drew calculations on an easel showing that raising the OEM price of Windows to $2,000 would inevitably reduce Microsoft's sales of Windows from 60 million to 15.8 million copies, but the higher price would also increase revenue tenfold from $3 billion to $31.6 billion. </i><br>
